problems.solutionCode:
public class Q2 {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("1. Consistency violated: Read-Your-Own-Writes (session consistency)");
        System.out.println("   User expects to see their own updates immediately");

        System.out.println("2a. Strategy 1: Read from primary after writes");
        System.out.println("   Trade-off: Increases primary load, reduces read-scaling benefit of replicas");

        System.out.println("2b. Strategy 2: Track last-write timestamp in session;");
        System.out.println("   wait for replica to catch up past that timestamp before reading");
        System.out.println("   Trade-off: Adds latency on reads; requires timestamp tracking");

        System.out.println("\nBonus: Strategy 3: Route all reads for a user to the same replica (sticky sessions)");
        System.out.println("   Trade-off: Uneven load distribution; session affinity complicates scaling");
    }
}

problems.description:
Implement leader election using Redis for distributed coordination.

```java
public class LeaderElection {
    private static final String LEADER_KEY = "scheduler:leader";
    private static final int TTL_SECONDS = 30;

    public boolean tryBecomeLeader(String nodeId) {
        // SET key value NX EX ttl — atomic: only succeeds if key doesn't exist
        Boolean acquired = redis.opsForValue()
            .setIfAbsent(LEADER_KEY, nodeId, Duration.ofSeconds(TTL_SECONDS));
        return Boolean.TRUE.equals(acquired);
    }

    public void renewLeadership(String nodeId) {
        // Only renew if still the leader
        String currentLeader = redis.opsForValue().get(LEADER_KEY);
        if (nodeId.equals(currentLeader)) {
            redis.expire(LEADER_KEY, Duration.ofSeconds(TTL_SECONDS));
        }
    }
}

// Usage:
if (leaderElection.tryBecomeLeader("node-1")) {
    runScheduledJob();
}
```

**Key insight:** `SET NX` (set if not exists) is atomic in Redis. TTL prevents eternal lock if leader dies. Renew every TTL/2 seconds. Used for cron jobs that should run on only one instance.

